		 <table cellpadding="2" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
		    <tr>
			  <td valign="top" align="left" class="info" colspan=2>
				  <b>Teagon</b> -&gt; <i> RE: EQ2, Firewalls, and NAT </i> (4/6/2005 5:24:14 AM)
			  </td>
			</tr>
	        <tr>
			  <td colspan=2 valign="top"><br>
		          <span class=msg>
                   There is only one viable solution, <br>  <br> Setup a tunnel between your office and an exterior computer; ie at home.  Change the port default of the IP tunnel to be port 80; or a standard port not being filtered.  With this done, you can assign local IP space to your office computer, setup a route to the SoE IP space to go through the tunnel, setup NAT translation on the office box to allow packets from soe to reach you. <br>  <br> This is the only means by which a person can bypass ingress/egress filtering of an internal network.  Its also the reason why networks requireing more indepth security will use a proxy requireing a login before any internet access is granted. <br>  <br> Describing the problem is easier than describing the solution.  Implementation would depend greatly on the resources available to you. <br>  <br> Teagon 
				  </span>
	          </td>
	        </tr>
	        <tr> 
